= Chapter 42: Rooming In <ch-rooming-in>

== THE QUICK ANSWER

Rooming in (keeping baby in your room 24/7) has real benefits for bonding and breastfeeding #citation[1]. But it can be exhausting when you're recovering from birth. If a nursery is available and you need rest, using it doesn't make you a bad parent.

== WHAT IT IS

Rooming in means your newborn stays with you around the clock rather than spending time in the hospital nursery. Most hospitals now default to this. Many Baby-Friendly hospitals have eliminated nurseries entirely.

The idea is simple: after nine months inside you, your baby transitions best when they stay close to you. Your smell, your voice, your heartbeat, your warmth — these are the only things your baby has ever known. Being near you is not just comforting, it is the most familiar and regulating environment your baby has.

That said, you also just went through one of the most physically demanding experiences of your life. The tension between what is ideal for baby and what is sustainable for you is real, and there is no single right answer.

