== BREASTFEEDING AND THE NURSERY: A CRITICAL WARNING

If you are planning to exclusively breastfeed and also want to use the nursery for rest, you need to have a very clear, explicit conversation with the nursing staff.

*The issue:* It is not uncommon for nursery staff to give a baby a bottle of formula without the mother's consent. This happens. Sometimes a nurse decides baby is "too fussy" and offers a bottle. Sometimes it is well-intentioned — they think they are helping you rest by not waking you. Sometimes it happens because the nursery is busy and a bottle is faster than bringing baby back to your room for a feeding.

*Why this matters for breastfeeding:*
- In the first days after birth, your body is learning how much milk to produce based on how often your baby nurses. Every feeding your baby gets from a bottle instead of from you is a missed signal to your body to make milk.
- Formula satisfies baby for longer than breast milk (it is harder to digest, so baby sleeps longer after a bottle). This can mean longer stretches without nursing — further reducing the signals your body needs.
- Even one or two formula bottles in the early days can interfere with breastfeeding establishment, especially if your milk has not fully come in yet.
- Nipple flow preference is real: bottles deliver milk faster with less effort than the breast. A baby who gets bottles early may become frustrated at the slower flow of nursing.

*What to do:*
- Tell the nursing staff directly: "Do not give my baby formula. Bring baby to me when hungry." Say it at admission. Say it at every shift change.
- Put it in your birth plan in writing.
- If the hospital uses a whiteboard in your room, write it there too.
- Ask your partner to reinforce this message, especially if you are asleep or groggy.
- If you are using the nursery overnight, specify: "Wake me to breastfeed. Do not supplement."

*If formula is medically necessary:*
There are legitimate medical reasons a baby might need supplementation — low blood sugar, excessive weight loss, jaundice requiring increased feeding. If the medical team recommends formula, ask them to explain why, and ask whether donor milk or syringe-fed colostrum could be used instead. The point is not to refuse all supplementation no matter what — it is to make sure it does not happen without your knowledge and explicit consent.

This is your baby, your body, and your feeding relationship. No one should make that decision for you while you sleep.

