== SAFETY AND OVERSIGHT

There is another benefit of rooming in that does not get talked about enough: when your baby is in your room, you and your partner can see everything that happens.

*Monitoring in real time:*
- You know who is coming in and out of your room and what they are doing with your baby
- You can ask questions about any procedure or test before it happens
- You can decline or delay things you have not consented to
- You are present for any assessments, and you can ask what the results mean

*Reducing errors and unwanted interventions:*
- Hospitals are busy, high-volume environments. Mistakes happen — wrong medication, wrong baby, wrong procedure. These are rare, but they are not zero.
- When baby is in the nursery, procedures may happen on autopilot: formula supplementation, a bath you did not want yet, tests done without your knowledge
- Staff are less likely to perform procedures you have declined when you (or your partner) are right there, awake, and paying attention

*Your partner as advocate:*
If you are resting, sleeping, or recovering from surgery, your partner can serve as the eyes and ears. When a nurse comes in to take baby for a test, your partner can ask: "What is this for? Did we consent to this? Can it wait?" This is not about being adversarial with your care team — it is about staying informed and involved in every decision about your newborn.

*A practical reality:*
None of this means the nursery is unsafe. Hospital nurseries are staffed by professionals who care for babies every day. But there is a difference between your baby being one of many in a nursery and your baby being right beside you, where you can see and hear everything. For parents who value that oversight, rooming in provides it.

