== PRACTICAL TIPS FOR ROOMING IN

*Set up your room for success:*
- Keep baby's bassinet right next to your bed, within arm's reach
- Have diapers, wipes, and a change of baby clothes within reach so you do not have to get up for every change
- Keep water and snacks at your bedside — you will need them, especially if breastfeeding
- Dim the lights at night to help both you and baby settle

*Manage the interruptions:*
- Ask the nursing staff to cluster care — meaning they do vitals, checks, and assessments all at once rather than waking you every hour for something different
- Put a sign on the door if your hospital allows it: "Mom and baby resting — please cluster care"
- Turn off your phone notifications. Visitors can wait. Sleep cannot.

*Know your limits:*
- If you have not slept in 36 hours and you feel like you cannot safely hold your baby, that is your body telling you something important
- If you are alone overnight and struggling, call the nurse. Many hospitals can have a nurse watch baby at the nurses' station for a stretch even if there is no formal nursery
- Falling asleep with baby in the hospital bed can be dangerous. If you are that tired, ask for help before it becomes a safety issue

*If your hospital does not have a nursery:*
- Ask if nurses can watch baby at their station for a stretch
- Have your partner take shifts holding baby while you sleep
- Ask about any postpartum support services available on the unit
- Consider having a family member come during the hours your partner needs to sleep

