== OUR TAKE

Rooming in is wonderful in theory — and often wonderful in practice too. But it is not a moral imperative, and we want to be honest about both the benefits and the trade-offs.

*The benefits are real.* Rooming in supports breastfeeding establishment, gives both parents the chance to learn baby's cues, lets your partner build confidence as a caregiver from day one, and keeps you involved in every decision about your baby's care. It also gives your new family something irreplaceable — those quiet, early hours together. The midnight feedings, the tiny noises, the first diaper disasters, the moments where you just stare at this person you made. Those hours in the hospital room are the beginning of your family's story.

*As a mom, your number one priority will be your baby's well-being — that instinct kicks in immediately and it is fierce.* But you cannot pour from an empty cup. You need rest to recover, to produce milk, to be emotionally present, and to be safe. Taking care of yourself is not selfish. It is how you take care of your baby.

*Partners — your focus should be on taking care of mom so she can take care of baby.* Bring her water. Handle the diaper changes. Hold the baby so she can sleep. Field the visitors. Ask the nurses questions so she does not have to. Run interference. Your job in those early hospital days is not just bonding with the baby (though that is important too) — it is making sure mom has everything she needs to recover and feed.

*Do not feel guilty if you need the nursery.* A few hours of real sleep can be the difference between coping and crisis. A rested mother is a safer, more present mother. That said, there are real, tangible benefits to rooming in — particularly for breastfeeding. If you can manage it (especially with a partner sharing the load), it is worth the effort. If you cannot, the nursery exists for a reason.

*Think about it from your baby's perspective.* You are your baby's whole world. You are the only thing that baby has ever known — your heartbeat, your voice, the rhythm of your breathing. For nine months, that was their entire universe. Being close to you, held by you, hearing you — that is the most comforting, regulating thing in their experience. When your baby is on your chest, they are home.

*One more thing worth knowing:* Your baby will sleep a lot in those first days. They just went through labor too — the same hours of contractions, pressure, and intensity that you did. They are exhausted and recovering, just like you are. Many parents are surprised by how much newborns sleep in the first 24-48 hours. Take advantage of those stretches. Sleep when baby sleeps is a cliche because it is true.

*The bottom line:* If you can room in, especially with your partner there to share the work, do it. The bonding, the breastfeeding support, the oversight, the family time — it adds up. But if you are running on empty and need a break, take the break. There is no trophy for suffering, and your baby needs you healthy more than they need you exhausted and heroic.

There is no shame in needing rest. A rested parent is a safer, more present parent.

